    What actually crashes?                                                      
    At cJSON.c:808 the parser attempts to copy the parsed characters into a     
    newly allocated output buffer (output = (unsigned char                      
    *)malloc(allocation_length + 1)). Since allocation_length was computed      
    based on an unbounded loop that never saw a closing quote,                  
    allocation_length becomes larger than the input length and larger than the  
    safe maximum the library expects. The subsequent memcpy/memmove writes      
    past the heap block, triggering the heap buffer overflow detected by the    
    runtime.                                                                    
                                                                                
    In short:                                                                   
                                                                                
     вЂў The malformed JSON string is unterminated.                               
     вЂў parse_string assumes a closing quote will eventually appear in the       
       buffer and never checks for endвЂ‘ofвЂ‘input before dereferencing            
       *input_end.                                                              
     вЂў The missing length check causes an infinite (but bounded by buffer       
       limits) walk that eventually reads/writes outside the allocated memory,  
       corrupting the heap and causing the crash.                               
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Minimal local fix (dropвЂ‘in patch)                                           
                                                                                
    Add a bounds check to the stringвЂ‘parsing loop so it stops when the end of   
    the supplied buffer is reached, rather than relying only on the backвЂ‘slash  
    guard.                                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     /* In cJSON.c, around line 798 (inside parse_string) */                    
     static unsigned char *parse_string(buffer *input_buffer)                   
     {                                                                          
         вЂ¦                                                                      
         const unsigned char *input_end = buffer_at_offset(input_buffer) + 1;   
         const unsigned char *input_start = input_end;                          
         size_t   length = input_buffer->length;                                
                                                                                
         /* Minimal addition */                                                 
         while (*input_end != '\"')                                             
         {                                                                      
             /* If we have walked off the end without finding the closing       
     quoteвЂ¦ */                                                                  
             if (input_end >= input_buffer->content + length) {                 
                 /* JSON text is malformed вЂ“ report failure */                  
                 goto fail;                                                     
             }                                                                  
                                                                                
             /* existing escapeвЂ‘sequence handling ... */                        
             if (input_end[0] == '\\')                                          
             {                                                                  
                 if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >=         
     input_buffer->length) {                                                    
                     goto fail;                                                 
                 }                                                              
                 вЂ¦                                                              
             }                                                                  
             input_end++;                                                       
         }                                                                      
         вЂ¦                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Effect: If the JSON is missing its closing quote (\"abc in the example),    
    the parser now falls out of the function via fail, which in turn returns    
    NULL and triggers the normal error handling path instead of corrupting the  
    heap.                                                                       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    More thorough rootвЂ‘cause fix                                                
                                                                                
    The minimal patch above stops the immediate crash, but it still leaves the  
    parser in a state where it can be given malformed JSON that silently        
    fails. A more robust solution addresses the invariant that every JSON       
    string must be properly terminated.                                         
                                                                                
    1. Integrate the length check into the loop condition                       
                                                                                
    Replace the raw while (*input_end != '\"') with a bounded loop:             
                                                                                
                                                                                
     while (input_end < input_buffer->content + length && *input_end != '\"')   
     {                                                                          
         вЂ¦                                                                      
     }                                                                          
     if (*input_end != '\"')   /* reached buffer end without closing quote */   
         goto fail;                                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
    2. Defensive duplicate of the length guard                                  
                                                                                
    Even though the guard in linesвЂЇ803вЂ‘806 already checks for a backslash, add  
    the same guard for the generic вЂњnot a closing quoteвЂќ path:                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     if ((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length)   
     {                                                                          
         goto fail;   /* outвЂ‘ofвЂ‘bounds read */                                  
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    3. Guard the allocation size                                                
                                                                                
    Before allocating the output buffer, verify that allocation_length does     
    not exceed a reasonable maximum (e.g., SIZE_MAX - 1) and that the final     
    size fits into a size_t safely:                                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
     if (allocation_length == 0 || allocation_length > SIZE_MAX - 1) {          
         goto fail;                                                             
     }                                                                          
     output = (unsigned char *)malloc(allocation_length + 1);                   
     if (!output) {                                                             
         /* memory allocation failure */                                        
         goto fail;                                                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    4. Clear the output buffer on failure                                       
                                                                                
    If malloc fails or any other failure occurs after memory has been           
    allocated, ensure that partiallyвЂ‘allocated blocks are freed to avoid        
    leaks.                                                                      
                                                                                
    5. UnitвЂ‘test guard                                                          
                                                                                
    Add a test case that feeds an unterminated string ("abc) to                 
    cJSON_ParseWithOpts. The test should assert that the function returns NULL  
    and sets an appropriate parseвЂ‘error code, confirming the fix works.         
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Summary                                                                     
                                                                                
     вЂў What went wrong: parse_string kept advancing input_end past the          
       supplied JSON buffer while waiting for a closing quotation mark that     
       never arrived. When it finally tried to allocate memory based on the     
       (nowвЂ‘incorrect) character count, it overвЂ‘allocated and later wrote past  
       the heap boundary, causing the reported heap buffer overflow.            
     вЂў Why the variables were set that way: input_end was only bounded by the   
       logic of finding \". Without a separate check for the bufferвЂ™s logical   
       end, the loop ran until the process hit unmapped memory. The lack of a   
       complementary length guard for the nonвЂ‘backslash case left the code      
       vulnerable.                                                              
     вЂў How to fix it: Insert a bounds check (or equivalent) before              
       dereferencing *input_end, and ensure the allocation size is sane.        
       Provide a clear failure path for unterminated strings.                   
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Handle unterminated JSON strings gracefully by adding a proper              
    endвЂ‘ofвЂ‘buffer test in the stringвЂ‘parsing loop; plus add defensive           
    allocations and error handling as shown above. This prevents the heap       
    overflow and yields deterministic error reporting instead of a crash.       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #### Recommendation                                                        
     * Minimal fix: add `if (input_end >= input_buffer->content +               
     input_buffer->length) goto fail;` inside the `while (*input_end !=         
     '\"')` loop.                                                               
     * Thorough fix: bound the loop by buffer length, duplicate the             
     lengthвЂ‘guard, validate allocation size, and ensure cleanвЂ‘up on any         
